sentences: Adam Freeland (born 7 August 1973) is an English record producer and DJ.
Born in Welwyn Garden City, Hertfordshire, England, he first began DJing in 1991, originally mixing deep house and later drum and bass.
After becoming an in-demand DJ around Britain, he released his first mix album Coastal Breaks (1996) and formed the electronic music duo Tsunami One with Kevin Beber.
From 1999 to 2001, Freeland  hosted a show on Friday night on London's Kiss 100 FM.
In 2000, he released his debut studio album, Now & Them.
On 14 April 2013, the band released their debut self-titled EP, along with a video for the track "Basic Instinct".
On 7 July 2014, the band released their debut album entitled Liminal on Infectious Music (UK) and Mute (US).
In 1996, Freeland released the first Coastal Breaks album, both of which are one track over an hour long each.
Freeland's debut artist album Now and Them, released in 2003, relied on influences from punk, hip hop, electro, dub, reggae and rock.
In 2008, Freeland contributed the song "KIN" to the Survival International charity album, Songs for Survival.
In July 2010, Adam released the single 'How To Fake Your Own Life' which included remixes by Etienne de Crecy and Om Unit.
Freeland's extended remix of Sarah Vaughan's "Fever" is used in the 2011 George Nolfi movie The Adjustment Bureau.

From 1999 to 2001, Freeland  hosted a show on Friday night on London's Kiss 100 FM.
In 2000, he released his debut studio album, Now & Them.
In 1996, Freeland released the first Coastal Breaks album, both of which are one track over an hour long each.
Freeland's debut artist album Now and Them, released in 2003, relied on influences from punk, hip hop, electro, dub, reggae and rock.

At the beginning of 2010, Cope™ Remixed was released on Freeland's own Marine Parade label, featuring all songs from the original Cope™ album but this time remixed by over twenty different producers, resulting in a double album covering a range of different electronic genres and sounds.
"Fear" was featured in the 2002/2008/2016 Dreamcast, PlayStation 2, Xbox 360 and PlayStation 4 title, Rez (known on the Xbox 360 as Rez HD and on the PlayStation 4 as Rez Infinite).
Freeland also created many custom tracks exclusively for the video game Juiced 2: Hot Import Nights.
On the video game The Sims 2: Nightlife, three songs ("Busy", "Arch of the Sims" and "Makeover") are credited to Freeland.
In the animated anthology film The Animatrix, the song "Big Wednesday" is credited to Freeland (as "Free*Land").
